## Context

Split from 0277 (RDJ-26561 R&R, tracker 0274, remark R1-14): the referee
suggests presenting a citation network drawn from the database "to
demonstrate its potential and/or limitations". The editor softened this
(ED-02) but the author DECIDED to implement it, by presenting the Œconomia
companion's co-citation analysis as a worked example of what the corpus
enables. The compute/plot pipeline already exists —
`scripts/figures/plot_fig_traditions.py` (Make target
`deliverables/_shared/figures/fig_traditions.png`, Makefile:458), backed by
`scripts/_pre2007_traditions.py`: top-250 pre-2007 references, Louvain
communities, anchor-author matching (method described in manuscript
appendix A.5). CAUTION (verified 2026-07-21): the PNG has never been
generated or committed, and no deliverable embeds it — the submitted
manuscript carries only @tbl-traditions; the sole embed is the ORPHANED
include `deliverables/_shared/_includes/cocitation-communities.md`
("Electronic Supplement figure" that never shipped). First render may
need layout fixes; eyeball before embedding (visual-verify norm).

The finding to feature (author's framing, grounded in manuscript.qmd
~line 114): the third intellectual tradition (international governance)
shows a gap between narrative and citation practice. Negishi — the
narrative anchor for welfare-weights burden-sharing — is absent from the
top-250 pre-2007 references. The community the algorithm detects is
anchored instead by North, DiMaggio and Finnemore, institutionalist and
constructivist literature. And the economists of treaty design who ARE
present (Barrett) co-cite with the FIRST tradition's carbon-pricing
cluster, not with the institutionalists — a division of intellectual
labour the network makes visible. This demonstrates both the corpus's
potential (the finding) and its limitations (pre-2007 sparsity, <50
works/year — the manuscript's own caveat), exactly what R1-14 asks for.

